title: Queensland teenager Oli Wardrope catches 2m snake before school | Perth Now
text:
Queensland teenager Oli Wardrope catches 2m snake before school Clare Armstrong, The Courier-Mail February 24, 2017 3:38pm 
A QUEENSLAND teen has wrangled a huge python from underneath his family’s ute on the way to school. 
A video of Oli Wardrope, 14, has been shared on Facebook showing him bravely climbing underneath the family’s Toyota Cruiser to retrieve a 2 metre long python tangled underneath. 
Oli slithered under the car to access the snake, which was wrapped around the undercarriage, before using his bare hands to trap and remove it. 
“I got his head,” Oli said to the people looking on, including his dad. 
The teen grabbed the snake’s head and rolled out from under the car before manoeuvring the reptile into a sack. 
“F***ing hell lad, that’s a big snake,” the man holding the sack said. 
Oli’s dad gives him a handshake for a “job well done”. 
“That’s my boy, been wrangling since he was five. 
“Just a morning before school for him,” his father wrote on the video.
